{{unreferenced|date=August 2016}}
{{italic title}}
'''''Playboy's Book of Forbidden Words''''' was first published in 1972 by [[Playboy (magazine)|Playboy Press]] and distributed by [[Simon & Schuster, Inc.|Simon & Schuster]]. Written by [[Robert Anton Wilson]], it is sub-titled '''''A liberated dictionary of improper English, containing over 700 uninhibited definitions of [[erotica|erotic]] and [[Scatology|scatological]] terms'''''. The paperback edition's cover featured [[Mercy Rooney]]. It is a collection of 'items' from "Abbess" to "Zoophilia Erotica".

Interviewed by ''Common Ground'', Vancouver (July 1999 Issue), Wilson talked about how he'd been tinkering with ''Playboy's Book of Forbidden Words,'' which he considered his best book—worst, that is, after the editors at ''Playboy'' did to the book "what the Roman Army did to the [[The Rape of the Sabine Women|Sabine women]]". Claiming ignorance and inexperience, he had not objected at the time. If he had later rewritten the book the way he had wanted it to be the first time, he would have called it ''Robert Anton Wilson's Book of Black Magick and Curses''. He aimed to include all the [[Anthropology|anthropological]] and [[Neuro-linguistic programming|neurolinguistic]] theorems that ''Playboy'' removed.
Portions of this work are reprinted (reedited by Wilson with an added explanation of his problem with ''Playboy'') in his 1988 work ''Coincidance''.

{{Robert Anton Wilson}}

